    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-01-01T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-01-01T00:00:00-05:00" n="233"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d233">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Roosevelt Papers</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Memorandum by the President</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-01-01">January 1,
                            1942</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>I told the Secretary of State I thought it inadvisable to resuscitate this
                    question by making a statement;<note n="1" xml:id="d233fn1">Presumably the draft
                        statement <hi rend="italic">supra.</hi>
                    </note> that the French Admiral has already declined to leave the St.
                    Pierre-Miquelon; that we cannot afford to send an expedition to bomb him out and
                    that Sumner Welles could best handle this situation verbally when he gets to Rio
                    on the above basis.<note n="2" xml:id="d233fn2">There is no evidence that this
                        question came up at the Conference of American Foreign Ministers held at Rio
                        de Janeiro, January 15–28, 1942. For documentation on that Conference, see
                            <ref target="frus1942v05#pg_6">
                            <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1942, vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">v</hi>, pp. 6</ref> ff.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>F. D. R.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
